         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translation</head>
            <div type="translation" source="#vitali1932" xml:lang="it"><p>Per la vittoria e la salute di Nerone Claudio Cesare e di tutta la sua casa, M. Antonio Gemello, 
               a spese del tempio di Apollo, (dedicò) ad Apollo Myrtoo.</p></div>
         <div type="translation" resp="#edd" xml:lang="en"><p>For the victory and the safety of Nero Claudius Caesar, 
               and his whole household, to Apollo Murtoos.
               M(arkos) Antonios Gemellos <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign xml:lang="la">M(arcus) Antonius Gemellus</foreign></supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">made the dedication</supplied> from the <supplied reason="subaudible">funds</supplied> of Apollo.</p></div>
         </div>
         
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>Apparently more or less a pair with <ref type="inscription" n="C.287">C.287</ref>; see discussion there for the date and the victory.</p>
            <!-- <p>See also 
               <bibl><author>Roscher</author> <title>Lexicon</title> s.v. Myrtous</bibl>;
               <bibl><title>PW</title> XVI s.v. Myrtates</bibl></p> -->
            <p>Line 4: For this epithet for Apollo at Cyrene see  <ref target="https://igcyr.unibo.it/igcyr006000">IGCyr006000</ref>; the  title may be purely local, see Callimachus, <title>Hymn to Apollo</title> 91 (at <ref target="http://data.perseus.org/texts/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0533.tlg016.perseus-grc1">Perseus</ref>); but cf. the appearance
               of Ἀπόλλων Μυρτάτης in Cyprus (most recently published as
               <title>SEG</title> 33.655, available at <title>PHI</title> <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/303521">PH303521</ref>). <!--  .see SEG 1196bis for Laronde on this .--></p>
            <p>Line 5: See on <ref type="inscription" n="C.287">C.287</ref> for his identity and the probable dating of his priesthood in CE 56/57.</p>
         </div>
         
